### P9: Lowest Common Ancestor of a BST (LC #235)

**Problem:** Find the LCA of two nodes p and q in a BST.

**Key Insight:** Use BST property — no need to explore the whole tree!

```
- If both p and q < root  → LCA is in the LEFT subtree
- If both p and q > root  → LCA is in the RIGHT subtree
- Otherwise               → root IS the LCA
```

```python
def lowestCommonAncestor(root, p, q):
    if p.val < root.val and q.val < root.val:
        return lowestCommonAncestor(root.left, p, q)
    elif p.val > root.val and q.val > root.val:
        return lowestCommonAncestor(root.right, p, q)
    else:
        return root    # split point = LCA
```

**Iterative version:**
```python
def lowestCommonAncestor(root, p, q):
    node = root
    while node:
        if p.val < node.val and q.val < node.val:
            node = node.left
        elif p.val > node.val and q.val > node.val:
            node = node.right
        else:
            return node
```

**Time:** O(h) | **Space:** O(1) iterative

